---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Lion King Uncovered — The Disney Deception — Nazaryah"
  description="Osiris, Horus, and Set — Egyptian religion animated scene for scene in the most beloved animated film of the 1990s."
>
  <div class="sw-wrap">

    <!-- ── HERO ── -->
    <section class="sw-hero">
      <a href="/disney" class="sw-back">&#8592; The Disney Deception</a>
      <p class="sw-label">&#8213; The Disney Deception &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="sw-title">The Lion King Uncovered</h1>
      <p class="sw-sub">
        Osiris, Horus, and Set — Egyptian religion animated for children
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── MODE BAR ── -->
    <div class="sw-mode-bar">
      <button id="btn-quick" class="sw-mode-btn sw-mode-active">&#9654; Quick Read</button>
      <span class="sw-mode-divider">&#8213;</span>
      <button id="btn-full" class="sw-mode-btn">Full Study</button>
    </div>

    <!-- ── QUICK READ PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-quick">

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-kicker">The most beloved animated movie of the 1990s. Millions of families own it. It's been a Broadway show for 25 years. Your kids can sing every song. It's also an almost word-for-word retelling of Egyptian religion.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Meet Osiris and Horus</p>
          <p>For three thousand years, Egypt's biggest religious story: A good king named Osiris is killed by his jealous brother Set. His infant son Horus has to be hidden to survive. The boy grows up in exile, comes back, fights his uncle, defeats him, takes back the throne. The land comes back to life.</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li><strong>Mufasa = Osiris</strong> (the good king, murdered by his brother)</li>
            <li><strong>Scar = Set</strong> (the jealous brother who takes the throne)</li>
            <li><strong>Simba = Horus</strong> (the hidden son who grows up in exile)</li>
            <li><strong>Sarabi = Isis</strong> (the widow queen who waits for her son)</li>
            <li><strong>Rafiki = the Egyptian priest</strong> (the shaman who paints symbols and talks to spirits)</li>
          </ul>
          <p>This is not a loose parallel. This is the same story, rebuilt with animals instead of people.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Opening Scene Is a Worship Service</p>
          <p>Watch the first four minutes again. The sun rises. Every creature gathers at Pride Rock. They bow. A priest-monkey holds a baby lion up to the sun while a choir sings in Zulu. Light shines down. Every animal lowers its head. That is a religious ceremony.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Romans 1:25</p>
            <p>"Who worshipped and served the creature more than the Creator, who is blessed for ever. Amen."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">'Circle of Life' Is Not a Christian Phrase</p>
          <p>The opening song teaches: that life and death are part of a great wheel, everything returns, the strong eat the weak, it's all balanced, it's all sacred. That's pantheism. That's Hinduism. That's every pagan religion in the ancient world.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Hebrews 9:27</p>
            <p>"And it is appointed unto men once to die, but after this the judgment."</p>
          </div>
          <p>You die once. Then judgment. There is no circle. Every time your children sing "Circle of Life," they're reciting a pagan creed with a great melody.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Simba Talks to His Dead Dad</p>
          <p>Simba looks up at the stars and Mufasa appears in the clouds. "Remember who you are..." That scene is the emotional heart of the movie. Most people cry. It's also necromancy.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Deuteronomy 18:10–11</p>
            <p>"...or a consulter with familiar spirits, or a wizard, or a necromancer."</p>
          </div>
          <p>The dead do not speak to the living. Not in real life. Not in Simba's life. King Saul lost his kingdom for doing exactly this (1 Samuel 28).</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What The Lion King Teaches Your Kids</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li>Everything is a circle — death, life, eating, being eaten. It's all holy.</li>
            <li>The dead watch you from the stars and speak to you.</li>
            <li>Identity comes from looking inside and "remembering who you are."</li>
            <li>Shamans with sticks are wise and helpful.</li>
            <li>Kings deserve worship from every creature.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>None of that is the gospel. All of it was ancient Egyptian religion.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-footer-quote">
        <div class="sw-summary-block">
          <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; The Short Version</p>
          <p class="sw-summary-text">The Lion King is the Osiris-Horus-Set drama of Egyptian religion — ancestor worship, animal worship, priestcraft, nature-religion — wrapped in a lion cub's coming-of-age story and sold as family entertainment.</p>
        </div>
        <p style="text-align:center; margin-top:1.5rem;">
          <button id="btn-full-cta" class="sw-mode-btn" style="font-size:0.75rem; letter-spacing:2px;">&#8594; Read the Full Study</button>
        </p>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-quick -->

    <!-- ── FULL STUDY PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-full" style="display:none">

      <!-- ── THE OSIRIS MYTH ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Osiris Myth</p>
          <p>The myth of Osiris is among the oldest religious narratives in recorded history. It appears in the Pyramid Texts, dated to approximately 2400 BC — making it more than four thousand years old. It is expanded in the Coffin Texts, the Book of the Dead, and preserved in its most complete literary form by the Greek writer Plutarch in his treatise On Isis and Osiris.</p>
          <p>The narrative: Osiris was the just and good king of Egypt. His brother Set was jealous. Set murdered Osiris, dismembered his body, and scattered the pieces across the land. Set then seized the throne. Osiris's wife Isis gathered the pieces, reassembled Osiris long enough to conceive a son — Horus. Horus was hidden in the marshes of the Nile delta to protect him from Set. The boy grew up in secret. He returned, challenged Set, fought a prolonged cosmic battle, and ultimately reclaimed his father's throne.</p>
          <p>From that point forward, every Pharaoh of Egypt was understood to be the living Horus on the throne — and when he died, he became Osiris in the afterlife. The myth was not a children's story. It was the state religion of the most powerful empire of the ancient world, preserved for three thousand years.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── SCENE FOR SCENE ── -->
      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Lion King Follows It Scene for Scene</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; The Parallel</p>
            <p>"Mufasa is Osiris. Scar is Set. Simba is Horus. Sarabi is Isis. Rafiki is the priest of Osiris. The only thing Disney changed was the species."</p>
          </div>
          <p>Mufasa is the good king, beloved by his kingdom, murdered by his brother. Scar rules with a dark hand — under his reign the Pride Lands descend into drought and famine, mirroring the Egyptian tradition that Set's rule brought desolation. Simba, the young heir, is driven from the kingdom under false guilt — his father's death blamed on him — which mirrors the Egyptian version in which Horus was targeted for destruction by Set and had to be hidden.</p>
          <p>Sarabi, the widow queen, waits. Rafiki is the shamanic priest — he paints symbols, communes with spirits, performs rituals, and is the one who finds Simba and sends him back. In the Egyptian tradition, the priest of Osiris was the keeper of the mysteries, the one who conducted the sacred rites and guided the heir to his destiny.</p>
          <p>The opening presentation of infant Simba at Pride Rock is the Egyptian coronation ceremony. The new Horus was presented to the priesthoods and the people of Egypt, anointed with sacred oil, and raised to the sun as recognition of his divine status as the living god-king.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── CIRCLE OF LIFE ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">'Circle of Life' Is a Pagan Doctrine</p>
          <p>The opening song does not simply celebrate nature. It articulates a specific cosmology: that all life moves in cycles, that death feeds life, that the predator and the prey are part of a sacred balance, that everything returns, that the universe is self-regulating through eternal recurrence. This is pantheism. It is present in ancient Egyptian religion, in Hinduism, in Stoic philosophy, and in every form of nature-worship that has ever existed.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Hebrews 9:27</p>
            <p>"And it is appointed unto men once to die, but after this the judgment."</p>
          </div>
          <p>Scripture teaches a linear view of reality. Creation has a beginning. Human beings die once. There is a judgment. There is a resurrection. There is a new heavens and a new earth. There is no circle. The circle is the pagan answer to the question of what happens after death — nothing is lost, it all returns, the wheel keeps turning. Scripture answers that question differently: the wages of sin is death, and after death, judgment.</p>
          <p>Disney's Circle of Life teaches that every death is natural and sacred, that the strong eating the weak is part of a holy order, that all beings are parts of one cosmic whole, and that the spirits of the dead watch over the living from the stars. Every one of those claims is explicitly contradicted by Scripture. Every one of them was affirmed by ancient paganism.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── THE PRESENTATION OF SIMBA ── -->
      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Presentation of Simba and the Worship of Nature</p>
          <p>The opening scene of The Lion King is staged as a religious event. Thousands of animals travel to Pride Rock. They bow. A baboon who functions as the high priest receives the infant, anoints his head, and presents him to the assembled worshippers. The sun breaks through at the moment of presentation. Every animal bows its head.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Romans 1:22–25</p>
            <p>"Professing themselves to be wise, they became fools, and changed the glory of the uncorruptible God into an image made like to corruptible man, and to birds, and fourfooted beasts... who worshipped and served the creature more than the Creator, who is blessed for ever. Amen."</p>
          </div>
          <p>The most famous opening scene in Disney history is every creature bowing to a lion cub while a priest holds him to the sun. The worship of the creature is not a subtext in this film. It is the opening act of worship. It is the image the film chose to begin with.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── ANCESTOR WORSHIP ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Ancestor Worship and the Ghost in the Sky</p>
          <p>The emotional climax of the film is Simba's encounter with his dead father. Mufasa appears to Simba in the stars — a visible spirit, speaking audibly, commissioning his son for action. Simba effectively prays to his dead father. The dead father appears. The dead father gives guidance. Simba's entire redemption arc pivots on this moment of communication with the deceased.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Deuteronomy 18:10–11</p>
            <p>"...or a consulter with familiar spirits, or a wizard, or a necromancer."</p>
          </div>
          <p>When King Saul consulted the witch of Endor to bring up the spirit of Samuel, it was the sin that sealed the destruction of his dynasty (1 Samuel 28). Yet Disney stages Simba's entire redemption arc — the moment that redeems the film, the scene every audience member remembers — around a conversation with a dead ancestor. In the Egyptian tradition, the dead Pharaoh-as-Osiris continued to watch over and guide the living Pharaoh-as-Horus. The Lion King faithfully reproduces this theological structure for Western children.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── CHRISTIAN COMPARISONS ── -->
      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What About Christian Comparisons?</p>
          <p>Pastors sometimes use The Lion King as a Christian allegory. Mufasa as the Father, Simba as the Son, the exile as a kind of death, the return as resurrection. This is backwards.</p>
          <p>The Lion King does not resemble the gospel because it was built on Christian themes. It resembles the gospel because the Egyptian Osiris myth was one of the primary pagan counterfeits of the gospel — a pre-figuring of the real story, drawn from the same deep human hunger for a just king who is murdered, a son who is hidden, and a restoration that renews the land. The enemy has been counterfeiting the gospel since before Moses.</p>
          <p>The Lion King is not pointing toward Messiah. It is pointing toward Horus. The fact that pagan counterfeits share structural similarities with the truth does not make them safe. It makes them more dangerous — because they scratch the itch without delivering the cure.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── WHAT IT TEACHES ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What The Lion King Teaches a Child</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li>The circle of life is the fundamental truth of existence. Death and predation are natural and sacred.</li>
            <li>The dead continue in the sky and can be communicated with through grief and meditation.</li>
            <li>Identity is discovered by looking inside and "remembering who you are" — not by submitting to Yahuah.</li>
            <li>The shaman is a wise guide whose mystical practices are presented as good.</li>
            <li>Monarchy is sacred, and every creature owes worship to the king.</li>
            <li>Personal redemption comes from within — Simba had to "remember" who he was, not repent or be forgiven.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The Lion King is the most theologically coherent Disney film in the canon — coherently Egyptian. Every major plot point, every major song, every major character maps to a specific element of the Osiris myth and the religious system that sustained Egypt for three thousand years.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── SUMMARY ── -->
      <section class="sw-footer-quote">
        <div class="sw-summary-block">
          <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; Summary</p>
          <p class="sw-summary-text">The Lion King is the Osiris-Horus-Set drama of Egyptian religion animated scene for scene — ancestor worship, animal worship, priestcraft, nature-religion, and the circle-of-life doctrine all wrapped in a lion cub's coming-of-age story and sold as family entertainment.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="sw-quote-text">"For from of old men have not spoken against those who worshipped and served the creature more than the Creator, who is blessed for ever. Amen."</p>
        <p class="sw-quote-ref">— Romans 1:25</p>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-full -->

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  const btnQuick = document.getElementById('btn-quick');
  const btnFull = document.getElementById('btn-full');
  const btnFullCta = document.getElementById('btn-full-cta');
  const panelQuick = document.getElementById('panel-quick');
  const panelFull = document.getElementById('panel-full');

  function showQuick() {
    panelQuick.style.display = '';
    panelFull.style.display = 'none';
    btnQuick.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnFull.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }
  function showFull() {
    panelFull.style.display = '';
    panelQuick.style.display = 'none';
    btnFull.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnQuick.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }

  btnQuick.addEventListener('click', showQuick);
  btnFull.addEventListener('click', showFull);
  if (btnFullCta) btnFullCta.addEventListener('click', showFull);
</script>

